  "text": "As can be appreciated in Fig. 3 , the reduction rates for both normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells followed zero-order kinetics at DQ concentrations of Ͼ10 M, the concentration range of the majority of the DQ concentration vs. time data in Figs. 1 and 4 . Thus, since most of the data in this range would Fig. 8 . In-gel zymography of normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell NQO1. A: normoxic (N) and hyperoxia-exposed (H) cell extracts containing 60 and 66 g of protein, respectively, were separated by nondenaturing gel electrophoresis and stained in a solution containing the NQO1 substrate 2,6-dichlorophenolindophenol, NADPH as the electron donor, and the tetrazolium dye MTT as the precipitating redox indicator, as described in MATERIALS AND METHODS. The arrow designates the band that was enriched when the NQO1 standard (50 ng of protein) was mixed with the normoxic cell extract before electrophoresis (NQO1 standard ϩ N). The NQO1 standard ϩ N, N, and H samples were run in duplicate on the same gel, the gel was cut in half before staining, and the second half, shown in B, was stained in the same staining solution except that dicumarol (10 M) was also included. C: NQO1 immunoblot obtained using eluates from an excised NQO1 standard and a normoxic cell zymography band, the latter selected based on comigration with the NQO1 standard in the zymography, as indicated by the arrow in A. Fig. 9 . Effect of DQ on KCN-insensitive oxygen consumption by normoxic (A) and hyperoxia-exposed (B) cells in the absence (solid lines) or presence (dotted lines) of dicumarol. The initial recordings are after the addition of KCN (2 mM; solid line) or KCN ϩ dicumarol (2 mM and 25 M, respectively, dotted lines) to the oximeter chambers. DQ (50 M) was added to the oximeter chambers at the times indicated by the arrows. Ferricyanide was added only to the chambers containing DQ without dicumarol (solid lines) at the times indicated by the arrows. Ferricyanide, DQ, or DQH2 alone did not stimulate oxygen consumption in the absence of the cells, and DQH2 alone did not stimulate oxygen consumption in the presence of cells [data not shown, [CITATION_1] ]. The reaction mixtures contained 49.3 and 51.3 cm 2 cell-coated bead surface area for the normoxic cells with DQ or DQ ϩ dicumarol, respectively, and 61.6 and 54.3 cm 2 for the hyperoxia-exposed cells with DQ or DQ ϩ dicumarol, respectively. The g of protein per cm 2 surface area were 29.9 and 29.7 for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells, respectively. not be sensitive to K m1 , the model was fit to the data in Fig. 3 again, this time with the K m1 for both conditions constrained to be the same (solid line). As seen in Fig. 3 , the model fits under the different assumptions are reasonably similar, most strikingly in the key zero-order concentration range (i.e., Ͼ10 M), again emphasizing the insensitivity of reduction rates in this range to K m1 . The estimated common K m1 was 3.4 M and the estimated V max1 with the common K m1 were 0.35 and 0.70 nmol per min Ϫ1 per cm 2 for NQO1-mediated DQ reduction by the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells, respectively. Comparison of these V max1 values to those estimated from the model fit when the K m1 were unconstrained, i.e., 0.32 and 0.73 nmol per min Ϫ1 per cm 2 for the normoxic and hyperoxiaexposed cells, respectively, makes the point once again regarding the insensitivity of the majority of the data pertinent to this study to K m1 .",
